# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cuba-national-baseball5-team
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2022-baseball5-world-cup] The **2022 Baseball5 World Cup** was the first edition of the Baseball5 World Cup, the mixed-gender Baseball5 (B5) world championship organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2022-baseball5-world-cup] It was held in Mexico City from 7 to 12 November 2022.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Cuba won the tournament, beating Japan in the final 2 matches to 0.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Chinese Taipei finished third defeating Venezuela 2 matches to 0 in the bronze medal game.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2022-baseball5-world-cup] 1There was no qualification event for WBSC Americas and WBSC Oceania.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2022-baseball5-world-cup] Teams were selected by World Baseball Softball Confederation.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2022-baseball5-world-cup] 2In October 2022, WBSC chose Hong Kong to replace Australia.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The **2024 Baseball5 Pan American Championship** was the first edition of the Baseball5 Pan American Championship, a Baseball5 tournament organized by WBSC Americas.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The championship was held from 27 to 30 June 2024, in the Domo Bolivariano in Barquisimeto, Venezuela and was contested between four national teams.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] Cuba went undefeated to win the tournament, finishing the opening round 6–0 and defeating Mexico in the championship game.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] Venezuela, that lost the semifinals against Mexico, claimed the bronze medal.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-pan-american-championship] The three teams qualified for the 2024 Baseball5 World Cup in Hong Kong.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The **2024 Baseball5 World Cup** was the second edition of the Baseball5 World Cup, the mixed-gender Baseball5 (B5) world championship organized by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-world-cup] It was held in Hong Kong from 7 to 12 October 2024.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The tournament was won by Cuba in their second straight Baseball5 World Cup title.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The Cuban team defeated Japan in the championship game, a replay of the 2022 final, 2 sets to 0 to finish the tournament undefeated with a 9–0 record.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-world-cup] Cuban players Briandy Molina and Haila González received the Male MVP and Female MPV of the World Cup.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-world-cup] France claimed the bronze after defeating Venezuela in the bronze medal game, 2 sets to 0.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The 2024 World Cup cost $12 million to host, with the Baseball Association of Hong Kong providing half of the funding.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/2024-baseball5-world-cup] The event has been given "M" Mark status (major sport event) by the Hong Kong government.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/australia-national-baseball5-team] The **Australia national Baseball5 team** represents Australia in international Baseball5 competitions.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/australia-national-baseball5-team] Australia was scheduled to take part in the inaugural Baseball5 World Cup held in Mexico City in November 2022, but the team did not participate and was replaced by Hong Kong less than one month before the beginning of the tournament.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/australia-national-baseball5-team] Australia made its Baseball5 World Cup debut in 2024 in Hong Kong.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/australia-national-baseball5-team] Trials were held in Victoria, New South Wales and Queensland to determine the squad that would play in the World Cup.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/australia-national-baseball5-team] Australia debuted with two defeats on the first day of the tournament against Mexico and Japan.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/australia-national-baseball5-team] The team finished last in Group B in the Opening Round, losing their remaining games against China, Tunisia and France.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto was founded in 1552 by Juan de Villegas, as a headquarters and to have better control of the territory believed to be rich in gold.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Its original name was **Nueva Segovia de Barquisimeto** and then it was shortened to just Barquisimeto.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] This city changed locations four times between 1552 and 1563.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] The original settlement was near the Buría River, but moved in 1556 due to frequent floods suffered by inhabitants.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] The second location was in the valley of the Turbio River, where the city stayed until Lope de Aguirre burned it down in 1561.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] The city was rebuilt 102 km (63 mi), but in 1562 they inhabitants asked for permission to move to another site due to strong winds blowing in the place.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Finally, Barquisimeto was moved to the north plateau of the Turbio River in 1563.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] During the country's independence, Barquisimeto joined the liberation movement and its deputy José Ángel Álamo signed the Independence Act on July 5, 1811.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] In 1929, the city went through a modernization program carried out by General Juan Vicente Gomez.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] He fixed the streets and avenues and buildings were built, like the Jacinto Lara Headquarters, the Government Palace and the Ayacucho Park.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] According to the German adventurer Nikolaus Federmann, the Caquetío aborigines used to call it Variquicimeto, which translates as "ash-colored river", the name with which the natives distinguished the water stream near the city.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] This river was named "Turbio River" by the Spanish conquerors, a name that is still in use today.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Another possible name origin is due to a red dye called *bariquí*.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] When Juan de Villegas founded it, he named the city "Nueva Segovia de Barquisimeto", but years later it became just "Barquisimeto", a word popularized by Oviedo y Baños in his book *History and Conquest of the Venezuelan Population*.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] The city's modern Cathedral of Our Lady of Mount Carmel is the cathedral of the episcopal see of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Barquisimeto.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] The Divina Pastora (Divine Shepherdess) is a statue of the Virgin Mary holding the infant Jesus, with a lamb at her side.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] It is considered to be one of the most important religious icons of Venezuela.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Divina Pastora is the patron saint of the city of Barquisimeto and of the Venezuelan National Militia.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Divina Pastora is celebrated in a procession on January 14 of each year, when a massive Marian procession occurs, considered to be one of the largest in the world, attracting thousands of pilgrims.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] The statue is removed from its shrine and is carried on the main streets of Barquisimeto in a procession which starts at the Iglesia de la Divina Pastora in Santa Rosa until it reaches the Barquisimeto Cathedral.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] This procession is unlike other mass Marian celebrations in the world, where the image does not leave its temple.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] This procession occurs due to the devotion the people of Barquisimeto have towards it as gratitude towards saving the city from a cholera outbreak that occurred in the city in the 19th century.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] In 2013, 3,000,000 faithful honored the Divina Pastora.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto is built on the terrace of the same name, on the banks of the Turbio River, about 600 meters (~2000 feet) above sea level, gradually sloping from 520 metres (1,710 feet) in the eastern part of the city to 700 metres (2,300 feet) in the west.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] To the northwest of Barquisimeto there are the Saroche hills (e.g.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Cerro Copeyal at 1323 meters a.s.l.) and to the northeast there are the Sierra de Aroa mountains (e.g.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Cerro Atravesado at 1712 meters a.s.l.).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto is located in central-western Venezuela, 363 km (226 mi) from Caracas, the country's capital city.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Being a point of convergence of major road and rail routes, it has a diverse economy and has grown into a large city of 930,000 inhabitants.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Its flat relief has enabled a systematic urban grid with streets numbered in ascending numerical order, and consistent signage that helps with locating addresses.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto has an average temperature of 25 °C (77 °F) throughout the year; its driest period is from December to March.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] In the city, a hot semi-arid climate (Köppen *BSh*) is dominant.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Located in that region, Barquisimeto records 550 millimetres or 21.7 inches of rain per year and its average temperature ranges 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] However, in higher regions near the Andes, temperatures are lower and the rain is more constant.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] For instance, in Sanare city, the annual average rainfall is 835 millimetres or 32.9 inches.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Barquisimeto is a city with a historic vocation by academic knowledge, and boasts a considerable sample of universities and institutes of higher education in Venezuela, has a high and growing student population from all over the country.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Major universities in the city include Universidad Centroccidental Lisandro Alvarado and Universidad Nacional Experimental Politécnica Antonio José de Sucre.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] The Transbarca system is a new "bus rapid transit" (BRT) system under construction, which was originally planned to use trolleybuses.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] When construction began, in 2006, the system was projected to serve an average of 170,000 people per day when completed, using 80 trolleybuses operating along 30 km (19 mi) of exclusive lanes, across the metropolitan area.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Service was planned to include an express route of 22 km (14 mi) along with one local route of 8 km (5 mi).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] With 52 stations, the BRT system is to include a centralized system of communication and security, and structures for easy access for elderly and disabled people.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] It is to be complemented with feeder routes, covering the areas of Greater Barquisimeto the BRT line will not serve, which will connect with the main line at terminal stations.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Although 80 articulated trolleybuses were purchased from Neoplan and delivered around 2008–09, the plans to operate the Transbarca system with those vehicles were dropped in 2013.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] In addition to reasons of cost, an inadequate supply of electricity with which to power the system was cited in the announcement of the decision.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] The city has an airport called Jacinto Lara International Airport.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] The city is home to several notable baseball and football teams.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/barquisimeto] Several other sports also have Barquisimeto as their home.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5-pan-american-championship] The **Baseball5 Pan American Championship** is the main Baseball5 tournament in the Americas, governed by WBSC Americas.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5-pan-american-championship] The top three teams qualify to the Baseball5 World Cup.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Mexico, a member of WBSC Americas, hosted the 2022 Baseball5 World Cup, the inaugural tournament of the Baseball5 World Cup.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Since there was no qualifying event for the Americas, Cuba and Venezuela were invited by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to join Mexico in the championship as the three teams representing the Americas.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5-pan-american-championship] The inaugural Baseball5 Pan American Championship was contested from 27 to 30 June 2024 in the Domo Bolivariano in Barquisimeto, Venezuela with four teams taking part: hosts Venezuela, Cuba, Mexico and Puerto Rico, who made its international debut in Baseball5 competition.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Cuba won the 2024 Baseball5 Pan American Championship undefeated, with a 6–0 opening round record, and beating Mexico 2 sets to 0 in the final.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5-pan-american-championship] Venezuela, that lost the semifinals against Mexico, was awarded the bronze medal.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Outs (eliminations) occur either when a hit ball is caught before it touches the ground by a defender, or (in specific situations) when a defender with the ball either touches the base a runner is supposed to reach, or touches the runner themselves.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Offensive players can also get themselves out by breaking the rules while hitting the ball or running the bases.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The teams switch roles after three outs are made, with an "inning" being completed when both teams have played offense once.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The game is played to five innings, with any ties being broken by playing extra innings as necessary, and games generally lasting 15 to 20 minutes.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Oftentimes, a best-of-three (or even best-of-five) series of "sets" is played to determine the result of a matchup between two teams.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Unlike baseball/softball, there is no pitcher, with the batter (offensive player who hits the ball) starting each play with the ball, which is the only equipment used in the game.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The WBSC proposed the game in 2017 with the intention of growing baseball/softball on a global level, claiming that the game's low cost, fast pace, and small field make it a more accessible and appealing entry point to those sports.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] It organizes a mixed-gender B5 World Cup for senior and youth players in alternating years, with teams required to field at least two active players per gender.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The game is also scheduled to be played in a mixed-gender format at the 2026 Summer Youth Olympics, and has started to find adoption in schools, national championships, and other international events around the world.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] B5 was inspired by similar games that have been played on the streets in Latin America and elsewhere for decades, such as cuatro esquinas (*four corners*) in Cuba and pelotica de goma (*little rubber ball*) in Venezuela.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In some cases, B5 significantly diverges from the rules of these games; for example, it does not feature a pitcher, as is done in one street variation in Colombia, and players are allowed to run the bases, as opposed to only walking, as is required in one version of "cuatro esquinas".
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Before B5, the WBSC had tried promoting several other baseball variants at a youth level, such as tee-ball, without significant success.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] B5 was invented in part to increase the odds that a sport similar to baseball and softball will be played in the Olympics, with B5 meant to contribute to an ultimate goal of having a billion fans in the baseball-softball community by 2030 and helping to demonstrate the global reach of the games.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] It also intended to create a game that would be more accessible and cheap, as the only equipment used in B5 is the rubber ball, and the field is much smaller than a baseball diamond or softball field, with the game being playable indoors.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In this respect, as well as the fact that there are fewer players required to play a game, B5 is meant to imitate smaller, more urban variants of other major sports, such as 3x3 basketball, futsal, and rugby sevens.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Inclusiveness is meant to be another goal of B5, with the game being scheduled to be the first mixed-gender team sport in an Olympic event to not have a separate competition for male-only or female-only teams.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In addition, the game is meant to be simpler to learn, have more youth appeal, and be more exciting, with players participating more frequently throughout the game.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Another claimed benefit is that with B5 being introduced across the entire world at the same time, no one country is likely to dominate the game; the lack of the pitcher role, which is highly specialized, contributes to this.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The first Baseball5 international competition took place at Foro Italico, Italy in 2018.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The game was demonstrated and played in various places across the world, such as in the United States during the MLB All-Star Week, in the 2021 Bulgarian Olympic Festival, and on the sidelines of the 2018 Summer Youth Olympics in Argentina and the 2020 Summer Paralympics in Japan.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The WBSC has tried to promote B5 for socially beneficial purposes as well, by taking it to places such as Jordan's Azraq refugee camp.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] It is being implemented in many schools in some countries, like Australia and France, and is now played in 83 countries.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In 2025, the WBSC celebrated May 5th (5/5) as "High5 for Baseball5" day.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Before the 2022 Baseball5 World Cup, a new B5 rulebook was published that increased clarity on some of the rules, as well as changing some of the field dimensions.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] For example, the bases were increased in size from 50 cm (20 in) to 60 cm (24 in), and were moved from the inner edge of the infield to the outer edge, increasing the distance between them by 0.5 metres (1 ft 8 in).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In 2025, a double base was added for home plate.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The infield is a 13 m (42.65 ft)-square, with a base in every corner.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The fair territory is a 18 m (59.06 ft)-square, with one of the corners coinciding with the home plate (the final base).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The batter's box is a 3 m (9.84 ft)-square.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] It is placed outside of the fair territory and is built on the extension of the two foul lines (which distinguish fair and foul territory, and sit in fair territory) crossing each other at the home plate corner; the lines are included as part of the batter's box area.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] All bases are marked on the ground (i.e. they are not physical cushions like in baseball/softball).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Ideal shape and size of the first three bases is a 60 cm (23.62 in)-square, and they are placed in the outfield (the part of fair territory outside of the infield).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In order to avoid collisions, the first base is "doubled" in foul territory, with the outer base referred to as the "safety base".
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Home plate also has a double base, known as the "safety plate", which can be found diagonally adjacent in the batter's box as a 90 cm (35 in) triangle.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The ideal height of the fences bounding the field is 1 m (3.28 ft).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] However, every league or tournament organisation may decide on other ways of limiting the field of play, such as using existing walls or marking the ground with lines.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The only piece of equipment used is a hollow rubber ball with a circumference of 208.4 mm (8.20 in).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The Visitor team starts the game in offense, with the Home team on defense.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The goal of the offensive team is to have each of its players hit the ball and then run counterclockwise around all four bases in order without being eliminated by the defense, thus scoring one run for their team.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The act of hitting takes place while a hitter is entirely in the batter's box; the hitter must not step out of the lines until the hit ball reaches fair territory, and must first signal which hand they will hit with.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] If these requirements are not met, or if the ball goes into foul territory before passing first or third base, then the batter is out.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The batter in the action of running towards first base, after putting the ball in play, has to touch the base in foul territory (the "safety base") except in circumstances where a collision could be avoided by going toward the base in fair territory.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] A runner (offensive player) who touches first base, second base, third base and home plate in that order scores one run for their team, and then leaves the field until their next turn as a hitter.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] When scoring, a runner must step on the safety plate rather than home plate, which is reserved for the defenders in order to avoid collisions.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Note: If a play occurs where the batter failed to legally hit the ball, then the play is canceled (i.e. any runners who got out or advanced around the bases during the play return to their bases as if the play never happened) and the batter is eliminated.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In teams with only five players, the first player "called out" (eliminated) in that inning becomes pinch runner on the base of the runner who is required to hit.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The batting order and the gender balance (in mixed-gender competitions) shall always be respected.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The five players (1st Base, 2nd Base, Midfielder, Shortstop, and 3rd Base, from right to left) of the defensive team shall all be in fair territory when the batter hits the ball.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The ball remains live if a defender with the ball leaves the field, so long as they secured possession of the ball in fair territory.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] If the ball leaves the court due to a defensive error (missed throw or missed catch of a thrown ball), each runner is awarded an extra base (i.e. the batter goes to 2nd base, and all other runners advance 2 bases as well).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Any runner who clearly advanced 2 bases before the defensive error may be granted an extra base as well (i.e. a runner on 1st who advanced to 3rd before the error can be awarded home plate).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The game ends at the end of the fifth inning if one team has scored more runs than the opponent.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Should the Home Team be ahead on the score after the Guest Team has completed its fifth offensive inning, the game is over and the Home Team wins.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Many B5 tournaments feature best-of-three series known as "matches" or "games", with each individual game in the series called a "game" or "set", and the team winning two sets being the winner of the overall match.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In case of a tie game, the teams shall play and complete extra inning(s) until one team scores more runs than the opponent.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In the sixth inning, the player scheduled to hit fifth (i.e. the player who batted last in the fifth inning, and whose name precedes the first batter of the sixth inning) is placed on first base as a runner to start the inning.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] In the seventh inning, the players scheduled to hit fifth and fourth are placed on first and second base respectively, and so on with three runners to start the following innings until the game ends.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] By WBSC regulations, the game ends if there is still a tie after 7 extra innings.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] A game is over if a team leads by 15 runs at the end of the third inning or by 10 at the end of the fourth.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] At the international level, B5 is administered by the World Baseball Softball Confederation (WBSC).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Within each country, it is administered by the national baseball and/or softball governing body.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Exceptions apply for certain countries, such as Japan, where a specific governing body has been set up to run B5.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The Baseball5 World Cup (B5WC) and Youth Baseball5 World Cup (YB5WC) are administered by the WBSC, with both tournaments alternating and happening every two years, and following the general format of having 50 games played between 12 national teams over 7 days.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] Continental qualifiers for each tournament will be played during their off-year.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/baseball5] The 2025 YB5WC will act as a qualifier for the mixed-gender Baseball5 event to be held in the Dakar 2026 Youth Olympic Games (YOG).
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/cuba-national-baseball5-team] The **Cuba national Baseball5 team** represents Cuba in international Baseball5 competitions.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/cuba-national-baseball5-team] They are the current World and Pan American Champions.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Baseball5 was inspired by similar games that have been played on the streets in Latin America and elsewhere for decades, such as "cuatro esquinas" (*four corners*) in Cuba.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Cuba, alongside Venezuela, were invited by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to represent WBSC Americas in the 2022 Baseball5 World Cup, held in Mexico City.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/cuba-national-baseball5-team] The Cuban team finished the tournament undefeated and won the final against Japan 2 matches to 0.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Briandy Molina was honored with the Outstanding Male Player Award and included in the All Star Team of the tournament.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Cuba won the 2024 Baseball5 Pan American Championship held in Barquisimeto, Venezuela.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/cuba-national-baseball5-team] The Cuban squad finished undefeated with a 6–0 record and defeated Mexico in the final 2 sets to 0, qualifying to the 2024 Baseball5 World Cup.
[src:cuba-national-baseball5-team/cuba-national-baseball5-team] Briandy Molina and Chaquira Azpiazu were awarded as the Most Valuable Players of the tournament, while manager Pablo Terry won the Best Coach Award.
